<file path="agentic/prompts/extraction/extract-figma-context.md">
 1: # Prompt: Extract Figma Context
 2: 
 3: This prompt is used to extract Figma tree nodes, variables, styles, and metadata into a stable node bundle.
 4: 
 5: ## Instructions for Agent
 6: 
 7: 1. **Do NOT generate HTML.** This phase is purely for data extraction.
 8: 2. **Do NOT choose final CSS classes.** Class resolution occurs in a downstream phase.
 9: 3. **Do NOT call Webflow MCP tools.** Webflow operations are forbidden during extraction.
10: 4. **Output Location**: All outputs must go to `workspace/figma/` directory.
11: 
12: ## Large Frame Policy
13: 
14: If the target frame is extremely large and contains complex sections:
15: 1. Extract top-level metadata first to identify section boundaries.
16: 2. Slice the frame by top-level sections.
17: 3. Re-run node extraction context for each section.
18: 4. Merge section bundles into a single cohesive `figma.node-bundle.json`.
19: 
20: ## Expected Output Files
21: 
22: - `workspace/figma/figma.node-bundle.json`: Raw node JSON tree and styles.
23: - `workspace/figma/metadata.json`: Frame name, dimensions, file version hash, and timestamp.
24: - `workspace/figma/variable-defs.json`: Figma variable collection definitions.
25: - `workspace/figma/screenshot.png` (optional): Visual screenshot of the frame.
26: - `workspace/figma/extract-run.log`: Execution log of the extractor.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/extraction/read-figma-data.md">
  1: # Prompt: Read and Analyze Figma Raw Data
  2: 
  3: ## Purpose
  4: 
  5: Produce a structured **design analysis document** BEFORE writing the HTML contract.
  6: This analysis is the mandatory input to `archive/deprecated-workflows/write-html-contract.webflow-first.md`. Do not skip this step.
  7: 
  8: Run AFTER:
  9: 1. Figma raw data is in `workspace/rawdata/`.
 10: 2. `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md` is read.
 11: 3. Per-project CF library loaded: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`.
 12: 
 13: Output file: `workspace/blueprints/[page-slug]_design-analysis.json`
 14: 
 15: ---
 16: 
 17: ## Why This Step Exists
 18: 
 19: Jumping from raw Figma JSON directly to HTML contract is error-prone on complex pages.
 20: This pre-analysis step forces systematic extraction of all decisions before naming begins:
 21: - Section inventory locks the vertical order and structural sizing choices.
 22: - Layout map decides every custom class name before the contract is written.
 23: - Typography catalog maps every text style to CF utilities once, consistently.
 24: - Color catalog verifies every color token is in the library before HTML is written.
 25: 
 26: ---
 27: 
 28: ## Output: Design Analysis JSON Structure
 29: 
 30: Write `workspace/blueprints/[page-slug]_design-analysis.json` with this shape:
 31: 
 32: ```json
 33: {
 34:   "page_slug": "home",
 35:   "figma_file_id": "...",
 36:   "generated_at": "ISO date",
 37:   "section_inventory": [...],
 38:   "layout_pattern_map": [...],
 39:   "typography_catalog": [...],
 40:   "color_token_catalog": [...],
 41:   "component_map": [...],
 42:   "responsive_notes": []
 43: }
 44: ```
 45: 
 46: ---
 47: 
 48: ## Section 1: section_inventory
 49: 
 50: For each top-level section frame (in vertical order on page):
 51: 
 52: ```json
 53: {
 54:   "section_id": "hero",
 55:   "figma_node_id": "123:456",
 56:   "figma_name": "Hero Section",
 57:   "order": 1,
 58:   "container_size": "large",
 59:   "padding_section_size": "large",
 60:   "background_token": "background-color-dark",
 61:   "has_dark_bg": true,
 62:   "notes": ""
 63: }
 64: ```
 65: 
 66: Rules:
 67: - `section_id`: slugify Figma frame name (lowercase, spaces→hyphens, drop special chars)
 68: - `container_size`: apply Section C thresholds from `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md`
 69: - `padding_section_size`: apply Section D thresholds
 70: - `background_token`: CF library class name, or `null` if no background token
 71: 
 72: ---
 73: 
 74: ## Section 2: layout_pattern_map
 75: 
 76: For each flex/grid layout frame inside sections:
 77: 
 78: ```json
 79: {
 80:   "section_id": "hero",
 81:   "layouts": [
 82:     {
 83:       "figma_node_id": "123:789",
 84:       "figma_name": "Content Row",
 85:       "direction": "horizontal",
 86:       "columns": null,
 87:       "gap_px": 48,
 88:       "gap_token": "gap-medium",
 89:       "cf_decision": "utility",
 90:       "suggested_utility_classes": ["flex-horizontal", "gap-medium"],
 91:       "suggested_custom_class": null,
 92:       "case": null
 93:     }
 94:   ]
 95: }
 96: ```
 97: 
 98: Rules:
 99: - `direction`: `"horizontal"` (flex row) | `"vertical"` (flex col) | `"grid"` | `"absolute"` (no auto-layout)
100: - `columns`: number if grid, `null` if flex
101: - `gap_token`: snap to nearest Layout token name (tiny/xxsmall/xsmall/small/medium/large/xlarge/xxlarge/huge/xhuge/xxhuge or semantic gaps small/regular/medium/large)
102: - `cf_decision`: `"utility"` when flex-horizontal/flex-vertical/gap-*/grid-N-col covers it; `"custom"` only when utilities can't express it
103: - `suggested_utility_classes`: if `cf_decision=utility`, list the classes; if custom, leave empty array
104: - `suggested_custom_class`: if `cf_decision=custom`, suggest the class name using Section G naming; if utility, leave `null`
105: - `case`: only set to `"Case 1"` if `cf_decision=custom`; `null` if utility
106: 
107: ---
108: 
109: ## Section 3: typography_catalog
110: 
111: One entry per distinct text style used on the page (not per-node):
112: 
113: ```json
114: {
115:   "style_id": "figma-style-id",
116:   "figma_style_name": "Heading/H1",
117:   "font_size_px": 64,
118:   "font_size_rem": "4rem",
119:   "font_weight": 700,
120:   "cf_heading_class": "heading-style-h1",
121:   "cf_size_class": null,
122:   "cf_weight_class": null,
123:   "cf_style_classes": [],
124:   "suggested_tag": "h1",
125:   "notes": "Sole H1 on page — no heading-style class needed, tag alone"
126: }
127: ```
128: 
129: Rules:
130: - Apply Section E algorithm from `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md`
131: - `cf_heading_class`: set if semantic/visual mismatch; `null` if tag alone is correct
132: - `cf_size_class`: set for body text sizes; `null` for headings
133: - `cf_weight_class`: set if weight utility needed; `null` if weight already in heading-style or is default
134: - `cf_style_classes`: array of any `text-style-*` utilities (allcaps, italic, etc.)
135: - `font_size_rem`: `font_size_px / 16`, keep as string with rem unit; exception: 14px = "0.875rem"
136: 
137: ---
138: 
139: ## Section 4: color_token_catalog
140: 
141: One entry per Figma color variable used on the page:
142: 
143: ```json
144: {
145:   "figma_variable": "colors/brand/Primary",
146:   "library_token": "primary",
147:   "text_class": "text-color-primary",
148:   "bg_class": "background-color-primary",
149:   "border_class": "border-color-primary",
150:   "usage_contexts": ["hero heading", "CTA button fill"]
151: }
152: ```
153: 
154: Rules:
155: - Apply Section F from `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md`
156: - Look up `figma_token` in `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`
157: - If ANY variable is NOT in the library → write a `blocker` entry and STOP. Do not proceed to HTML contract until PM resolves.
158: - If a Figma color is a hardcoded hex with no variable mapping → flag as blocker; operator must add to library first before writing HTML contract.
159: - Never hardcode hex values anywhere in the analysis or contract.
160: - **Dark Mode note:** Dark Mode is a variable collection mode (Theme collection, `mode-61994c14-2f10-542b-e084-a014a8caf47a`). Classes remain identical — the Theme variable resolves differently in Dark Mode. Document `dark_mode_value` per token for reference but do not create separate classes for dark mode. The same `text-color-primary` class works in both modes.
161: 
162: ---
163: 
164: ## Section 5: component_map
165: 
166: One entry per Figma component type used (not per-instance):
167: 
168: ```json
169: {
170:   "figma_component": "Button/Primary",
171:   "cf_pattern": "button",
172:   "variant_class": null,
173:   "instances_count": 3
174: },
175: {
176:   "figma_component": "Button/Secondary",
177:   "cf_pattern": "button",
178:   "variant_class": "is-secondary",
179:   "instances_count": 1
180: }
181: ```
182: 
183: ---
184: 
185: ## Section 6: responsive_notes
186: 
187: Flag elements that need breakpoint treatment:
188: 
189: ```json
190: {
191:   "element_class": "hero_content-row",
192:   "desktop": "flex row, 2 columns",
193:   "tablet": "flex column, 1 column",
194:   "mobile": "flex column, full width",
195:   "hide_at": null,
196:   "requires_breakpoint_custom_class": true,
197:   "case": "Case 4",
198:   "notes": "2-col → 1-col at tablet; width 100% on mobile"
199: }
200: ```
201: 
202: Rules:
203: - `requires_breakpoint_custom_class`: **Default `false` for spacing/type** — variable modes handle responsive shifts automatically. Set `true` only for structural reflow (column count, hide/show, complex positional changes that utilities can't express).
204: - `hide_at`: `"tablet"` | `"mobile-landscape"` | `"mobile-portrait"` | `null` → maps to `hide-*` utility
205: - If element is hidden at a breakpoint, use `hide-*` utility (NOT a custom class)
206: - For column reflow (e.g., 3-col desktop → 1-col mobile), use `grid-N-col-tab` / `grid-N-col-mobile` utilities — NOT a custom class; set `requires_breakpoint_custom_class: false`
207: 
208: ---
209: 
210: ## Validation Checklist Before Proceeding to HTML Contract
211: 
212: Run through this checklist after producing the analysis JSON. Do NOT proceed to `archive/deprecated-workflows/write-html-contract.webflow-first.md` until all pass:
213: 
214: - [ ] Every `section_id` is unique (no duplicate slugs)
215: - [ ] Section order in `section_inventory` matches Figma vertical order (top to bottom)
216: - [ ] Every color variable used on the page has a matching `library_token` in `color_token_catalog` — if any are missing, STOP and request library update from PM
217: - [ ] Every layout frame has a `suggested_class` in `layout_pattern_map` (no layout without a class name)
218: - [ ] `typography_catalog` covers every distinct text style visible on the page
219: - [ ] `component_map` covers every Figma component type used
220: - [ ] No hex values appear anywhere in the analysis JSON
221: 
222: ---
223: 
224: ## Source References
225: 
226: - `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md` — Sections A–G (node types, layout, sizing, typography, colors, naming)
227: - `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json` — project token classes
228: - `knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json` — global CF utility catalog
229: - `workspace/design-system.json` — project-specific REM scale
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/extraction/sync-design-system-from-figma.md">
 1: # Prompt: Sync Design System from Figma
 2: 
 3: This prompt describes how to validate and synchronize the Figma variable collections and styles against the Client-First CSS contract.
 4: 
 5: ## Context
 6: 
 7: This phase runs after the Figma extraction node bundle is saved. You must read from the extraction files directly (`workspace/figma/figma.node-bundle.json` and `workspace/figma/variable-defs.json`). Do NOT make live Figma MCP requests.
 8: 
 9: ## Strict Sync Rules
10: 
11: 1. **Strict Token Matching**: Every design system token (colors, spacing, font weight) used in the design frame must match a corresponding allowed variable in the Client-First Library Contract.
12: 2. **Missing Token = Blocker**: If a Figma variable or theme alias cannot be resolved to an allowed CSS variable, flag it as a `blocker` and stop the pipeline.
13: 3. **No Automatic Class Proposals**: If a styling value is missing or untokenized, the sync tool must NOT propose new classes or variables.
14: 4. **No Hardcoded Hex/Rem Values**: All properties must resolve to variable-backed Client-First classes. Hardcoded spacing or color values on elements are blockers.
15: 
16: ## Sync Report Output
17: 
18: Write the sync report to `workspace/reports/design-system-sync-report.json` with the following structure:
19: - `timestamp`: Sync runtime.
20: - `matched_tokens`: Mapped variable names and target CSS variables.
21: - `missing_tokens`: List of Figma variables that are missing in the CSS contract (leads to failure).
22: - `unmapped_styles`: List of style guides or styles not mapped.
23: - `hardcoded_values`: List of layers containing raw color/spacing overrides.
24: - `blockers`: List of blocker errors.
25: - `status`: `"pass"` | `"failed"` (fails if any blockers or missing tokens exist).
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/normalization/normalize-figma-nodes.md">
 1: # Prompt: Normalize Figma Nodes
 2: 
 3: ## Role & Context
 4: You are a Figma tree normalizer agent. Your job is to clean up a raw Figma extraction tree (`figma.node-bundle.json`) before it is passed to Semantic IR, preparing it to align strictly with the Client-First CSS contract.
 5: 
 6: ## Normalization Instructions
 7: Perform the following corrections on the Figma node hierarchy:
 8: 
 9: 1. **Generic Layer Names Recovery**:
10:    - Detect layer names like `Frame 1234`, `Group 55`, `Rectangle 1`.
11:    - Infer their structural/logical purpose from their children. E.g., a frame holding a single text node could be named `wrapper-text`, and a group of buttons could be named `button-group`.
12:    - Avoid generic Figma naming outputs in normalized nodes.
13: 
14: 2. **Style Variables & Color Snapping**:
15:    - Look for raw values in node properties (fills, strokes, text styles).
16:    - Resolve raw hex/rgba values using the CSS contract allowed variables. Calculate Euclidean distance (using HSL/RGB properties) and snap any color within a threshold of 15 units to the closest CSS variable.
17:    - If a color cannot be snapped to any variable in the contract, flag it as a blocker/warning.
18: 
19: 3. **Layout & Auto Layout Recovery**:
20:    - Identify frames that do not have active layout properties.
21:    - Infer their layout properties (flex directions: horizontal/vertical, gap sizes) from bounding box positions of children.
22: 
23: 4. **Ambiguous Media**:
24:    - Flags vector nodes, groups of curves, or shapes lacking content tags. Determine if they represent decorative icons, illustrations, or content images, and annotate them accordingly.
25: 
26: 5. **Repeated Subtrees**:
27:    - Scan children groups for identical layer structures/types indicating repeated item arrays (e.g. grids of cards, list items). Mark them as candidate components.
28: 
29: ## Output Constraints
30: - Write output to `figma.normalized-tree.json`.
31: - Output validation statistics and blocker details in `figma-normalization-report.json`.
32: - Block compilation if unresolved styles or untokenized raw color values are found.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/normalization/normalize-figma-to-semantic-ir.md">
 1: # Prompt: Normalize Figma to Semantic IR
 2: 
 3: ## Role & Context
 4: You are a Semantic IR compiler agent. Your task is to process a normalized Figma node hierarchy (`figma.normalized-tree.json`) and transform it into a structured Semantic IR tree (`figma.semantic-tree.json`).
 5: 
 6: ## Mapping Logic
 7: Convert each node into a semantic node with standard fields:
 8: - `id`, `name`, `type`
 9: - `role`: identify the semantic role of the element.
10:   - Heading levels: `heading-1` through `heading-6`
11:   - Body text: `paragraph`, `span`, `blockquote`
12:   - Blocks/Containers: `section`, `component`, `container`, `wrapper`, `list`, `list-item`
13:   - Interactive elements: `button`, `link`, `input`, `form`, `dropdown`, `slider`
14:   - Media: `image`, `icon`, `vector`
15: - `tag`: The resolved HTML tag.
16: - `classes`: Array of verified classes from the contract.
17: - `styles`: Snapped color/spacing properties.
18: - `media`: Descriptive properties for any media element (kind, role, alt text, asset ref).
19: 
20: ## Strict Policy
21: - Fail compilation if any node has a confidence score below 0.60.
22: - All styles must be fully mapped to CSS variables or tokens.
23: - No new classes may be proposed or invented.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/README.md">
 1: # agentic/prompts/
 2: 
 3: Agent prompts are grouped by pipeline stage.
 4: 
 5: | Folder | Purpose |
 6: |---|---|
 7: | `extraction/` | Prompts for reading Figma data, extracting context, and syncing design system variables |
 8: | `normalization/` | Prompts for normalizing Figma nodes and converting to Semantic IR |
 9: | `resolution/` | Prompts for resolving HTML tags, selecting Client-First classes, and generating the CSS library |
10: | `webflow/` | Prompts for building Webflow sections from native ops and QA-ing the built DOM against HTML blueprint |
11: 
12: ## Pipeline Flow
13: 
14: ```
15: extraction/ → normalization/ → resolution/ → (HTML rendered locally) → webflow/
16: ```
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/resolution/generate-cf-library.md">
  1: # Prompt: Generate Client-First Library from Figma Variables
  2: 
  3: ## Purpose
  4: 
  5: This prompt template guides the LLM to auto-generate or update
  6: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json` and
  7: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/figma-token-map.json`
  8: from raw Figma variable data extracted via Figma MCP `get_variable_defs`.
  9: 
 10: Run `python scripts/update_library_from_figma.py --site-id <id>` first
 11: to get the step-by-step instruction block before using this template.
 12: 
 13: ---
 14: 
 15: ## Input
 16: 
 17: - Figma variables output from: `get_variable_defs(figma_file_id="<id>")`
 18: - Current library (if exists): `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`
 19: - Current token map (if exists): `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/figma-token-map.json`
 20: 
 21: ---
 22: 
 23: ## Naming Rules
 24: 
 25: ### CF Category from Figma variable type / path
 26: 
 27: | Figma variable path contains | CF category |
 28: |---|---|
 29: | `color` / `colours` / `brand` / `palette` | → generates THREE classes: `text-color-*`, `background-color-*`, `border-color-*` |
 30: | `spacing` / `gap` / `padding` / `margin` | `spacing` |
 31: | `font-size` / `text-size` / `size/text` | `font-size` |
 32: | `font-weight` / `weight` | `font-weight` |
 33: | `radius` / `border-radius` | `border-radius` |
 34: | `opacity` / `alpha` | `opacity` |
 35: 
 36: ### Semantic name derivation
 37: 
 38: 1. Take the **last path segment** of the Figma variable path.
 39: 2. Lowercase and slugify (replace spaces with `-`, strip special chars).
 40: 3. Examples:
 41:    - `colors/brand/Primary` → `primary`
 42:    - `spacing/Large` → `large`
 43:    - `font-size/Body Default` → `body-default`
 44: 
 45: ### Full class name = `{cf_category}-{semantic_name}`
 46: 
 47: Examples:
 48: - `colors/brand/Primary` → `text-color-primary`, `background-color-primary`, `border-color-primary`
 49: - `spacing/Large` → `spacing-large`
 50: - `font-size/Body Default` → `font-size-body-default`
 51: 
 52: ### Unit conversion
 53: 
 54: - Spacing/font-size in px → divide by 16 → rem string
 55:   - `48px` → `"3rem"`
 56:   - `14px` → `"0.875rem"`
 57: - Colors: keep as hex, e.g. `"#FF5733"`
 58: - Font-weight: keep as number string, e.g. `"700"`
 59: - Border-radius in px → rem (same ÷16 rule)
 60: - Opacity: keep as decimal string, e.g. `"0.5"`
 61: 
 62: ---
 63: 
 64: ## Output Format
 65: 
 66: ### figma-token-map.json
 67: 
 68: ```json
 69: {
 70:   "figma_file_id": "<id>",
 71:   "updated_at": "<ISO8601>",
 72:   "naming_convention": {
 73:     "pattern": "{cf_category}-{semantic_name}",
 74:     "categories": ["text-color","background-color","border-color","spacing","font-size","font-weight","border-radius","opacity"]
 75:   },
 76:   "mappings": {
 77:     "colors/brand/Primary": {
 78:       "figma_value": "#FF5733",
 79:       "cf_text_class": "text-color-primary",
 80:       "cf_bg_class": "background-color-primary",
 81:       "cf_border_class": "border-color-primary"
 82:     },
 83:     "spacing/Large": {
 84:       "figma_value": "48px",
 85:       "cf_class": "spacing-large",
 86:       "rem_value": "3rem"
 87:     }
 88:   }
 89: }
 90: ```
 91: 
 92: ### client-first-library.json
 93: 
 94: ```json
 95: {
 96:   "project_id": "<site_id>",
 97:   "webflow_site_id": "<site_id>",
 98:   "figma_file_id": "<figma_file_id>",
 99:   "version": "1.0.0",
100:   "updated_at": "<ISO8601>",
101:   "classes": {
102:     "text-color-primary": {
103:       "figma_token": "colors/brand/Primary",
104:       "cf_category": "text-color",
105:       "webflow_property": "color",
106:       "value": "#FF5733",
107:       "description": "Primary brand text color"
108:     },
109:     "background-color-primary": {
110:       "figma_token": "colors/brand/Primary",
111:       "cf_category": "background-color",
112:       "webflow_property": "background-color",
113:       "value": "#FF5733",
114:       "description": "Primary brand background color"
115:     },
116:     "border-color-primary": {
117:       "figma_token": "colors/brand/Primary",
118:       "cf_category": "border-color",
119:       "webflow_property": "border-color",
120:       "value": "#FF5733",
121:       "description": "Primary brand border color"
122:     },
123:     "spacing-large": {
124:       "figma_token": "spacing/Large",
125:       "cf_category": "spacing",
126:       "webflow_property": "padding",
127:       "value": "3rem",
128:       "description": "Large spacing token"
129:     }
130:   }
131: }
132: ```
133: 
134: ---
135: 
136: ## Update Rules (when library already exists)
137: 
138: 1. **If class exists** → UPDATE `value` only. Preserve `description`, `figma_token`, `cf_category`, `webflow_property`.
139: 2. **If class is new** → ADD with full schema (all required fields).
140: 3. **If Figma token removed** → DO NOT delete class automatically. Flag it in changelog with `source: "figma_removed"` and ask PM.
141: 4. **Always** write a changelog entry for every changed or added class.
142: 
143: ---
144: 
145: ## Changelog Entry Format
146: 
147: ```json
148: {
149:   "timestamp": "<ISO8601>",
150:   "class": "text-color-primary",
151:   "old_value": null,
152:   "new_value": "#FF5733",
153:   "source": "figma_sync",
154:   "reason": "Initial generation from Figma variables"
155: }
156: ```
157: 
158: `source` values: `figma_sync` | `manual_edit` | `figma_removed`
159: 
160: ---
161: 
162: ## Validation After Writing
163: 
164: Run mandatory gate before any Webflow sync:
165: 
166: ```cmd
167: python scripts/gates/validate_project_library.py --site-id <site_id>
168: ```
169: 
170: Gate must return exit 0 before proceeding to sync.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/resolution/resolve-client-first-classes.md">
 1: # Prompt: Resolve Client-First Classes
 2: 
 3: ## Role & Context
 4: You are the Client-First Class Resolver. Your job is to select the correct classes for elements in the Figma Semantic IR tree based strictly on the generated Client-First library contract.
 5: 
 6: ## Class Resolution Priority
 7: Select classes using the following hierarchy (highest priority first):
 8: 1. **Component Base Class**:
 9:    - The primary identifier for a component (e.g. `nav_component`, `card_component`).
10: 2. **Component Variant**:
11:    - Modifier combo classes indicating variants (e.g. `is-secondary`, `is-dark`).
12: 3. **Client-First Utility Classes**:
13:    - Utility helpers for layout and spacing (e.g., `padding-global`, `container-large`, `margin-bottom-medium`, `text-size-regular`).
14: 4. **Webflow Native Classes**:
15:    - Pre-existing native classes defined by Webflow (e.g., `w-checkbox`, `w-form`).
16: 5. **Structural Conventions**:
17:    - Essential structural wrapper classes (e.g., `page-wrapper`, `main-wrapper`).
18: 6. **Blocker**:
19:    - If no class matches and strict mode is active, block compilation and report the unresolved styling node. Do not invent class names.
20: 
21: ## Restrictions
22: - All final classes must be verified against `allowed_classes` or `allowed_combo_classes` in the `client-first-library-contract.json`.
23: - Inline styles and hardcoded color values are strictly prohibited.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/resolution/resolve-html-tags.md">
 1: # Prompt: Resolve HTML Tags
 2: 
 3: ## Role & Context
 4: You are the HTML Tag Resolver. Your job is to assign the most semantically appropriate HTML tags to elements in the Figma Semantic IR tree.
 5: 
 6: ## Tag Resolution Priorities
 7: Assign tags based on the following prioritizations (highest priority first):
 8: 
 9: 1. **Component Registry**:
10:    - If a node is identified as a registered component (e.g. Navigation component), use its default tag (e.g. `nav` or `header`).
11: 2. **Explicit Figma Prefixes**:
12:    - Check if the layer name has explicit tag prefixes (e.g. `[nav]`, `[section]`, `[h1]`, `[button]`).
13: 3. **Normalized Role**:
14:    - Match standard roles directly to tags based on `tag.rules.yaml` (e.g. `heading-1` -> `h1`, `paragraph` -> `p`, `button` -> `a` or `button`).
15: 4. **Text Purpose**:
16:    - Check if a text block serves as a title, paragraph, link, input label, or simple inline style.
17: 5. **Control/Media/List Context**:
18:    - If parent or siblings form a list structure, use `ul`/`ol` and `li`.
19:    - If element behaves as input control, map to `input`, `select`, or `textarea`.
20: 6. **Parent Context**:
21:    - Maintain structural hierarchies (e.g., direct children of `ul`/`ol` must be `li`).
22: 7. **Fallback**:
23:    - Default to `div` for structures and `span` for inline text elements.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/webflow/build-webflow-section-native.md">
 1: # Prompt: Build Webflow Section Native
 2: 
 3: ## Role & Context
 4: You are the Webflow Section Builder. Your job is to execute a compiled Webflow Native Build Plan (`native-build-plan.json`) for a target page and section.
 5: 
 6: ## Operating Rules
 7: 
 8: 1. **Branch-First Deployments**:
 9:    - Ensure you are working on the designated temporary site branch (e.g. `refactor/html-first-compiler-revised`). Do not push changes to the main site layout.
10: 2. **Preflight Smoke Call**:
11:    - Make a preflight check using the style tool to confirm connection status and branch write authorization.
12: 3. **Strict Serialization**:
13:    - Execute all mutations sequentially. Do not trigger parallel element builder executions.
14: 4. **Audit Logging**:
15:    - Output log entries for every modification to the audit file `write-audit-log.jsonl`.
16: 5. **No whtml_builder**:
17:    - Use only fine-grained native operations (e.g., `create_element`, `create_style`). Do not use HTML layout parsers or raw markup injectors.
18: 6. **No Auto-Publish**:
19:    - Never call publish tools. Leave publishing to the manual closeout gates.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/webflow/qa-webflow-against-html.md">
 1: # Prompt: QA Webflow Against HTML
 2: 
 3: ## Role & Context
 4: You are the Webflow QA gatekeeper. Your job is to verify that the deployed Webflow site branch mirrors the approved local HTML section chunks.
 5: 
 6: ## QA Mandates
 7: 
 8: 1. **DOM Parity Check**:
 9:    - Compare the DOM structures of the sliced local HTML section chunks with the corresponding Webflow element subtrees.
10:    - Verify that tags, attributes, and classes match.
11: 2. **Class Check**:
12:    - Ensure that every class deployed on the Webflow elements exists in the Client-First library contract.
13:    - Fail QA if any custom class has been injected that was not pre-authorized.
14: 3. **Lineage Traceability**:
15:    - Verify that elements retain `data-section`, `data-component`, and `data-figma-node` properties pointing back to the original Figma nodes.
16: 4. **Style Auditing**:
17:    - Ensure no inline styles are present. All colors and dimensions must resolve to CSS variable contract tokens.
</file>

