<file path="agentic/knowledge/client-first-library.md">
  1: # Client-First Library
  2: 
  3: The Client-First library is split into two layers:
  4: 
  5: - `knowledge-base/client-first-theory.md`: human-readable rules and rationale.
  6: - `knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json`: structured class, property, and Figma signal catalog for agents and scripts.
  7: 
  8: ## How Agents Use It
  9: 
 10: 1. Read Figma raw data from `workspace/rawdata/`.
 11: 2. Match Figma signals against `knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json`.
 12: 3. Choose the Client-First class strategy:
 13:    - required global class,
 14:    - utility selection,
 15:    - utility pair,
 16:    - variable-backed utility,
 17:    - custom section,
 18:    - custom component,
 19:    - combo class.
 20: 4. Write the decision into `workspace/blueprints/*.json`.
 21: 5. Copy the same selected classes into Webflow build actions after user approval.
 22: 
 23: ## Class Mapping Rule
 24: 
 25: Every mapped class in a blueprint must include:
 26: 
 27: - `figma_property`
 28: - `figma_value`
 29: - `client_first_class` or `client_first_class_pattern`
 30: - `webflow_property`
 31: - `reason`
 32: - `source`
 33: 
 34: Example:
 35: 
 36: ```json
 37: {
 38:   "figma_property": "vertical section padding",
 39:   "figma_value": "80px top and bottom",
 40:   "client_first_class": "padding-section-medium",
 41:   "webflow_property": "padding-top and padding-bottom",
 42:   "reason": "Section-level vertical rhythm maps to the Client-First section padding utility.",
 43:   "source": "knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json"
 44: }
 45: ```
 46: 
 47: ## Multi-Project Library Workflow
 48: 
 49: Each Webflow project can have a dedicated Client-First library variant stored in
 50: `knowledge-base/libraries/{webflow_site_id}/`. This decouples project-specific
 51: token values (colors, spacing, typography) from the global CF methodology rules.
 52: 
 53: ### Library files per project
 54: 
 55: | File | Purpose |
 56: |---|---|
 57: | `client-first-library.json` | CF class → CSS property map (source of truth for Webflow sync) |
 58: | `figma-token-map.json` | Raw Figma variable → CF class name mapping |
 59: | `changelog.json` | Audit trail of every class value change |
 60: 
 61: ### How agents use per-project libraries
 62: 
 63: 1. Read `workspace/meta.json` → get `webflowSiteId`.
 64: 2. Load correct library via `tools/library_resolver.py:load_library(root, site_id)`.
 65: 3. Match Figma signals against `figma-token-map.json` first; fall back to global
 66:    `knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json` for structural/layout decisions.
 67: 4. Write class decisions into `workspace/blueprints/*.json` with `source` pointing
 68:    to the per-project library path.
 69: 5. After approval: sync library to Webflow via `scripts/sync_library_to_webflow.py`.
 70: 
 71: ### Updating a library from Figma
 72: 
 73: ```cmd
 74: python scripts/update_library_from_figma.py --site-id <webflow_site_id> --figma-file-id <id>
 75: ```
 76: 
 77: Follow the printed instructions: call Figma MCP → apply `agentic/prompts/generate-cf-library.md`
 78: rules → validate → sync.
 79: 
 80: ### Registry
 81: 
 82: `knowledge-base/libraries/registry.json` indexes all projects. The quality gate
 83: (`scripts/gates/run_quality_gate.py`) auto-runs `validate_project_library.py` when
 84: `workspace/meta.json` contains a `webflowSiteId`.
 85: 
 86: ---
 87: 
 88: ## Webflow Project Sync
 89: 
 90: The Webflow project should contain matching variables and global classes before build execution:
 91: 
 92: - page and main wrappers,
 93: - section, padding, and container classes,
 94: - text-size, heading-style, text-weight, and text-align utilities,
 95: - text-color, background-color, and border-color utilities backed by variables,
 96: - component custom classes generated from the approved blueprint.
 97: 
 98: If a mapped utility class does not exist in Webflow, the operator must record the missing class in `workspace/error-logs.json` and ask PM before creating or substituting it.
 99: 
100: ### New Classes in a Parallel Build
101: 
102: Not every Figma value maps to an existing Finsweet/CF class, so a build sometimes needs new custom
103: classes. These are decided up front by the architect (listed as `new_classes` in the blueprint) and
104: created once by the **parent operator in Phase 2A**, then registered into the per-project
105: `client-first-library.json` + `changelog.json` (`source: "figma_adapt"`). Because one author names and
106: creates them serially before any subagent runs, two sections can never invent conflicting names.
107: 
108: `section-builder` subagents in Phase 2B stay strictly apply-only: a class missing from the canvas is a
109: blocker recorded in `workspace/error-logs.json`, never a self-creation.
</file>

